Final Project Quantative Methods in Plant ecology

1 Research Interest:

The Interest of this work lays in reproducing the analysis and the corresponding graphical output from the ordinations shown in the paper: “The response of vegetation to chemical and hydrological gradients at a patterned rich fen in northern Alberta, Canada” published by Vitt et al in 2022. Their research aimed at understanding the relationship between the chemical composition and level of the surficial water and the plant community patterns of a patterned rich fen in northern Alberta Canada. The hypotheses, results, and interpretations by Vitt et al (2022), linked to the ordinations, will be included. The ordinations were done using NMDS and the bray-curtis simillarity index. More than only reproducing this, different modeling options will be assessed. More explicitly the two following questions will be answered:

    1. How do different modeling options like using a global or local model change the results?
    1. is Bray-Curtis the most suitable index for the analysis or do alternative indices produce better results?

Finally since my interest is specifically into bryophytes I will explore ordinations using only bryophyte species for the community matrix and compare them to ordinations only using vascular species.

2 Hypothesis

The authors present two hypothesis:

    1. Both hydrological and chemical gradients and plant communities have distinct spatial distributions across the fen
    1. there are close linkages between hydrological and chemical gradients and plant communities and their distributions.

Although a large part of the analytical methods used in the research by Vitt et al. is not included in this work, the Ordinations and the environmental vectors are linked to both of these hypothesis and at least support them. The objective of the ordination analysis specifically is stated in the paper as “To determine if plant community changes occur across the fen”.

4 Data

The dataset of the research was kindly provided by the main author of the paper Dale H. Vitt, Distinguished University Scholar, Professor and Chair Emeritus, School of Biological Sciences, Plant Biology, Southern Illinois University. It was sent on the 12th January of 2023.

In their analysis Vitt et al. looked at the McClelland Wetland. The patterned area contained within the wetland is 6.6 km long, 2.5 km wide, and 720 ha in extent, with an elevational gradient from 300.4 to 292.8 m. They examined the easternmost portion of the patterned area of the wetland, within an area of approximately 420 ha (58% of the entire patterned area).The exact study site is located at 57º27′01.81′′ N, 111º25′35.90′′ W.

The area was divided into 64 plots and for each plot measurements were done at the nearest string and flark. 100 total species were recorded. The Species abundance was estimated for each string and flark as percent cover within a 2-meter diameter circular sampling plot. So each value gives the abundance of a species for the string or flark within a plot. Water chemistry as well as plant community patterns were recorded. The water samples were collected from the 20th to 28th of August, 2018 in a depth of 0 to 7 cm.


4.1 Community Dataset

The Community matrix should contain 128 columns, corresponding to 64 plots with two two records each (string and flark) and 100 rows corresponding to 100 recorded species.

4.1.2 Data type, and omitting descriptive rows

We can also see that the first row has an NA value for all columns except the first two. In these two we have descriptive data, which we do not need for our analysis. We can therefore get rid of the first row for all columns. If we look at row 60 of the reactable above, we can see that there is one more line of descriptive data (“Bryophytes”), of which we can get rid off.

All columns are of the data type integer, except the first two. The first one rightfully is of type character, because its the species name column, the second one on the other hand should be integer as well, since its just like the other columns representing the species abundance. The reason it is saved as a character variable is that there is additional information in text form given in the first row of this column. We will transform the data type to be integer as well.

# cleaning rows and correcting data type 

 # omit rows 1 (descriptive data)

  Com$X0S <- as.integer(Com$X0S)

4.2 Environemntal Data

The environmental data should consist of 64 rows for the 64 different plots and eight columns: one for the plot number (1 to 64), one for the prescribed Spatial Area (1 to 5) and six for six different chemical attributes of the surficial water. The chemical attributes are:

  • Ca..mg.L. for Calcium ions in mg per L
  • K..mg.L. for Kalium ions in mg per L
  • Mg.mg.L for Magensium ions in mg per L
  • Na..mg.L for the Natrium ions in mg per L
  • pH for pH value
  • EC..µS.cm. for electrical conductance in µS per cm

5 Pre-Asessing simmilarity indexes

5.1 Correlation environmental and community data by distance

As we want to find an alternative index to the Bray-Curtis index, we will use the rankindex function, which ranks correlations between dissimilarity and gradient separation based on a community matrix and its corresponding environmental matrix.

# Spearman Rank Correlation between Env and Com 

  # for Flarks
  rankindex(Env,Com_F,c("euc","man","gow","bra","kul"),stepacross=F,method="spearman")
##       euc       man       gow       bra       kul 
## 0.4979615 0.5247986 0.3610160 0.5182511 0.5190304
  # for Strings
  rankindex(Env,Com_S,c("euc","man","gow","bra","kul"),stepacross=F,method="spearman") 
##       euc       man       gow       bra       kul 
## 0.1265351 0.1929627 0.1583393 0.1444553 0.1417355
  # for all
  rankindex(Env_Full,Com_Full,c("euc","man","gow","bra","kul"),stepacross=F,method="spearman") 
##        euc        man        gow        bra        kul 
## 0.14229324 0.11105282 0.10013059 0.09771893 0.09802047

We can see that the Bray-Curis disimillarity index performs at the middle to lower end regarding the correlation with the environmental dataset. For the string and flark dataset the manhattan dissimilarity index performs best and for the full dataset the euclidean distance matrix correlates best. We will use these indexed for further analysis and compare the results they produce.

5.2 Checking stress with dimensions

5.2.1 Building stress plot function

Next we want to take a look at the stress values in relation to the depicted dimensions. For better differentiation, we update the original function “dimcheckMDS” of the package “goeveg”, so it shows the dataset and index used in the title.

# Changing original dimChecmMDS function from goeveg package so it displays the matrix and distance 

dimcheckMDS_with_info <- function(matrix, distance = "bray", k = 6,  trymax = 20, autotransform = TRUE, trace= 0) {
  if(!is.data.frame(matrix)) {
    matrix <- data.frame(matrix)
  }
  stress <- 0

  for (i in 1:k) {
  nmds_i <- metaMDS(matrix, distance = distance, k = i, trymax = trymax, engine = "monoMDS", autotransform = autotransform, trace = trace)
  stress[i] <- nmds_i$stress
  }
# only part changed is to paste the Name of the Matrix and distance type in the title:
  plot(seq(1,k,1), stress, main=paste("Stress value in tested dimensions","\n",deparse(substitute(matrix)),"with", deparse(substitute(distance)), "distance"), xlab="Dimension", ylab="Stress",
       ylim=c(0,0.3), type="n")
  lines(seq(1,k,1), stress)
  points(seq(1,k,1), stress, pch=21, col="black", bg = "red", cex = 1.2)
  abline(0.2, 0, col="red", lty = 2)
  print(stress)
}

6 Creating Ordinations

In this next code chunk we will create ordinations for the 3 datasets using the 2 different indices, using a random start or a pre defined start and with a local or global model. This results in 3x2x2x2 = 24 ordinations.

set.seed(3)
# Building all MDS wih bray and man distance and use them as previous.best
# 2 dimensions, 25 tries and no transformation

 
# global model

 # Building NMDS for full dataset and a global model
    
    MDS_Com_Full_bray_g <- metaMDS(Com_Full, distance = "bray", k=2, try = 25, autotransform = FALSE,trace=FALSE, model = "global")
    
    MDS_Com_Full_alt_g <- metaMDS(Com_Full, distance = "euc", k=2, try = 25, autotransform = FALSE,trace=FALSE, model = "global")
    
    # with defined starting point (previous best)
    
    MDS_Com_Full_bray_pb_g<-metaMDS(Com_Full, previous.best=MDS_Com_Full_bray_g,trace=FALSE, autotransform = FALSE, k=2, try = 25, 
                                    model = "global", distance = "bray")
    
    MDS_Com_Full_alt_pb_g<-metaMDS(Com_Full, previous.best=MDS_Com_Full_alt_g, trace= FALSE, autotransform = FALSE, k=2, try = 25,

We can clearly see the difference in methodology regarding local and global models: “global is normal non-metric MDS with a monotone regression,”local is non-metric MDS with separate regressions for each point”. All ordinations for the full and the flark dataset achieve a very good fit to the data of over 0.9 both for the non-metric and the linear fit. For the string dataset the values are generally lower.
We can also see that the local model performs better or the same in all cases and for both metrics. For the string and flark dataset the Bray-Curtis index performs better than the manhattan distance. For the full dataset the euclidean distance performs slightly better than the Bray-Curtis index.

8 Creating functions to plot the ordination

We will create several functions to be able to more easily built the plots and also for future use.


8.1 Functions to get chars from the right or left of a string

The following code implenets two functions to retrieve the n most left or right characters from a string. We will use these to plot specific text, retrieved from the dataset.

substrRight <- function(x, n){
  # Trims down values in vector x to n char
  sapply(x, function(xx)
    substr(xx, (nchar(xx)-n+1), nchar(xx))
  )
}


substrleft <- function(x, n){
  # Trims down values in vector x to n char
  sapply(x, function(xx)
    substr(xx, (1), nchar(xx)-nchar(xx)+n)
  )
}

8.1.1 Function to create an ordination plot

Now we can implement function to further work with our built Ordinations. This function will use the function envfint to fit the environmental data onto our Ordination. Then it will build a ggplot. The parameters for this function are as followed:

  • NMDS = Ordination
  • Env = Environmental dataset
  • Plot_group = Vector attributing the Spatial area to all of our 64/128 points
  • colour_base = colours used to visualize the spatial areas (same length as number of spatial areas)
  • shape_base = shapes used to visualize the spatial areas (same length as number of spatial areas)
  • xlim and ylim = set up x axis and y axis
  • add_s_F = boolean to signal if the plot should include specification of S for String and F for Flark for each point
  • Env_output = “only” for only showing and creating the Env. output, True for showing and False for not showing the output
  • limit_env = string vector specifying the Environmental variables to include (must be same as in colnames of Env)
  • legend_position = “left”, “top”, “bottom” or “right”
# Creating function to 

Luis_gg_mds_env <- function(NMDS, Env, Plot_group, colour_base, shape_base, xlim = c(-1,1), ylim =c(-1,1), 
                            add_S_F = FALSE, Env_output = FALSE, limit_env= "No", legend_position = "right") {
  
  
  
 # First fit NMDS with ENV data    
  Env_model <-envfit(NMDS,Env,permu=999,na.rm=T)            
  
# if env_output = "only just print the env model and then abort the function
  
  
 if (Env_output == "only")
 {
        print(Env_model) 
 }
  # Plot using the plot group for colour, shape and fill 
 else
 {
  # Access and calcuate variables necessary for plotting arrows 
  Env_model_vec <- as.data.frame(Env_model$vectors$arrows*sqrt(Env_model$vectors$r))
  
  Env_model_vec$variables <- rownames(Env_model_vec)
    Env_model_vec$pvalues <- Env_model$vectors$pvals

    
# if we want to subset the environmental variables we can use the limit_env variable for that
    # check if limit_env was changed
  if(limit_env[1] != "No") 
  {
    # subset the environmentel model data by the names given in limit env
    Env_model_vec <- Env_model_vec[limit_env,]
  }
    
    
 
  Env_model_vec_long <- data.frame(
    NMDS1 = Env_model_vec$NMDS1*1.2,
    NMDS2= Env_model_vec$NMDS2*1.2,
    variables= Env_model_vec$variables
    )
  
  
  # Rescale NMDS values
  NMDS_scores_df<- data.frame(
    MDS1 = rescale(NMDS$points[,1], to = c(-1,1)),
    MDS2 = rescale(NMDS$points[,2], to = c(-1,1))
    
                              )
      

     
 gg <- ggplot(data = NMDS_scores_df ,aes (x= MDS1 ,y = MDS2 ,
                                     color =as.factor(Plot_group), 
                                     shape =as.factor(Plot_group), 
                                     fill= as.factor(Plot_group),
                                     size = as.factor(Plot_group))
         )+
    
    
    
    # Add title to plot
    
      ggtitle(
        
        # depending on method used change title accordingly
        
        if(NMDS$call[9]!="Null()")  # if previous best was not used
        {
          
                 paste(" Ordination of", NMDS$data,"with", NMDS$call[9], "model and\n", NMDS$call[8], "used as previous best") 

        }
        
        else                        # if previous best was used
       {
                 paste(" Ordination of", NMDS$data,"with", NMDS$call[8], "model and\n", NMDS$distance, "simillarity used") 

        }
       
       
      )+
      
    
    
    # Add points
    
      geom_point()+ 
      
    
    
    # Setting the up the legend and values of the scales
    
      scale_color_manual(name = "Group", labels= c("SP 1","SP 2","SP 3","SP 4","SP 5"), values=colour_base)+
      scale_fill_manual(name = "Group", labels= c("SP 1","SP 2","SP 3","SP 4","SP 5"),values=colour_base)+
      scale_shape_manual(name = "Group", labels= c("SP 1","SP 2","SP 3","SP 4","SP 5"),values=shape_base)+
      scale_size_manual(name = "Group", labels= c("SP 1","SP 2","SP 3","SP 4","SP 5"),
                        values=c(3.5,3.5,3,3,3))+
  
    
    
    # Legend design
    
      theme(legend.position = legend_position,  # Legend position
            legend.title  = element_text(color = "blue", size = 14, hjust = 0.5),  # legend title
            legend.background = element_rect(size=0.5, colour ="black"))+ # legend border
     
    
    
      # Plot background
    
      theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill= "white", colour= "black"))+ 
     
  
    
    
      # setting up the axis
    
      coord_cartesian( xlim =xlim, ylim =ylim)+
      
    
    
       # clearing the axis
    
      theme(axis.line=element_blank(),
            axis.text.x=element_blank(),
            axis.text.y=element_blank(),
            axis.ticks=element_blank(),
            axis.title.x=element_blank(),
            axis.title.y=element_blank())+
      
    
    
     # adding the env factor arrows
    
      geom_segment(data = Env_model_vec_long,
                   aes(x = 0, xend = NMDS1, y = 0, yend = NMDS2),
                   arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.25, "cm")),
                   colour="black",
                   inherit.aes = FALSE)+
      
    
    
      # adding the text to the arrows 
    
         geom_text(data = Env_model_vec_long,
                   # position text depending on the direction of the arrow
                  aes(x = NMDS1+(if (NMDS1[1]>=0){0.05}else {-0.05}), 
                      y=NMDS2, 
                      label = variables),
                  size = 4, 
                  inherit.aes = FALSE,
                  )+
       
    
    
      # add Stress text on the top right
    
         annotate( # if clauses for the case of inverted axis
                "text", x=xlim[2]+if (xlim[1]>=0) {0.15} else {-0.15}, 
                 y=-if (ylim[2]<ylim[1]){-ylim[2]}  else ylim[1], 
                 label= paste("2D Stress:",round(NMDS$stress,2)), 
                 size = 3.5,
                fontface = "bold"
                )+
        
    
    
      # if add_S_F was set to TRUE add S / F to all points
    
          if (add_S_F) {
        geom_text(data= NMDS_scores_df, 
                  aes(
                      x= MDS1, 
                      y= MDS2-0.05, 
                    # get one char from the right of the row names of the original data used 
                      label =substrRight(row.names(get(paste(NMDS$data,sep = ""))),1) 
                      ),
                  inherit.aes = FALSE,
                  size = 2.8
                )
      }
  
  
 
 # print the environmental model if the condition was set when calling the function
 
  if (Env_output == TRUE)
  {
    print(Env_model) 
  }
  

 # print the plot
 gg
  }

}

9.2.2.1 Full dataset:

Authors observation:

Flarks (left side of ordination Fig. 6a) ordinate vertically along water chemistry vectors (EC, Ca2+), while strings (right side of ordination) form a widely scattered group distributed along both x and y axes. Flarks from Spatial Areas 1 and 2 form a tight cluster toward the lower left, while Spatial Areas 3–5 flarks form more scattered groups to upper left (Fig. 6a).

Using local model:

The main observable difference is that using the local model the main Sp 1-2 flark cluster is more tightly packed. The main observations do not change.

9.2.2.2 Flark dataset:

Authors interpretation:

Flark plots are distributed widely on the ordination of ‘flarks only’ (Fig. 6c), with plots from Spatial Areas 1–2 placed to the right on the ordination and those from Spatial Areas 3–5 to the center and left. Spatial Area 1 is particularly distinctive.

Using local model:

No noteworthy difference.

9.2.2.3 String dataset:

Authors interpretation:

String plots occur intermixed in the ordination of ‘Strings only’ (Fig. 6b), with considerable variation within each spatial area; however, Spatial Areas 1–2 string plots are, in general, located to the left of the ordination, while those from spatial Areas 3–5 are located to the upper right.

Using local model:

For the string dataset we can see that with the local model we receive an ordination seemingly easier to interpret. The spatial area 1 and 2 points seem to be more clearly seperated from the majority of points belonging to groups 3 to 5. Also the general differentiation between points of areas 1 and 2 seems to be orthogonal to the environmental factors. This seems to better represent the findings of Vitt et al. regarding the distribution of the level of water parameters: “Spatial Areas 1–2 were lower in all surface water parameters compared to those from Spatial Areas 3–5”. Looking at the findings by Vitt et al. in Fig. 5, we can see that SP 1 and have a lower range in cation levels compared to Sp 3 to 5. This is also more clearly represented using the local model.

The most noticeable result can be seen for the string dataset. The r2 values are all higher and the p-values lower using the manhattan index. 10 Species abundances on the Full dataset

After assessing the different options for the ordinations. The next part focuses only on replicating the produced plots from Vitt et al. focusing on specific species and plotting them onto the ordination of the full dataset. The ordination using a global model and a a pre defined starting point seems to most closely match the ones by Vitt et al.

10.1 Creating a function

# creating a function called Luis_gg_mds_species
Luis_gg_mds_species <- function (NMDS, Plot_group, species_name_underscore, colour_base, xlim = c(1.25,-1.25), ylim= c(0.85,-1.05))
  
{
  

  
  
  # Setting up a data frame with our NMDS points data and adding the Plot group number 
  # and the Species abundance data for our wanted species 
  
    # binding data frame of the NMDS points and the plot group
  Spe_MDS<- cbind(data.frame(NMDS$points),Plot_group) 
    # accessing the original data used for the NMDS and   the column of the wanted species
  Spe_MDS$species <- get(paste(NMDS$data))[[(paste(species_name_underscore))]] 
  
  
  # Creating the Plot
  
    # for the base ggplot, we use the Plot group for our fill (colour) and the species abundance for the size scaling
  
  gg <- ggplot(data = Spe_MDS, aes(x = MDS1 ,y = MDS2,fill= as.factor(Plot_group),size=species))+ 
      
    
    # adding points with X = NMDS1 and y= NMDS2 
    
        geom_point(
          
          color = "black", pch=21 
          
          )+ 
        
    
    
    # fill legend, scaling and legend title (name)
    
        scale_fill_manual(
          
          name = "Group", 
          
          labels = c("Sp 1", "Sp 2", "Sp 3", "Sp 4",  "Sp 5"), 
          
          values = Col_base,
          
          guide = guide_legend(override.aes = list(size= 3))
          
        )+
        
    
    
    # size legend, scaling and legend title (name)
    
        scale_size( 
          
          labels  = c(
            round(max(Spe_MDS$species)/10,0),
            
            round(
              (
                (max(Spe_MDS$species) - round(max(Spe_MDS$species)/10,0))
                /3+  round(max(Spe_MDS$species))/10)
              ,0),
            
            round( 
              2* (max(Spe_MDS$species) - round(max(Spe_MDS$species)/10,0))/3  +  round(max(Spe_MDS$species))/10
              ,0),
            max(Spe_MDS$species)
            ),  # legend labeling 
          
          
          range = c(0,35), # size range                    

         
          breaks  = c(
            round(max(Spe_MDS$species)/10,0),
            
            round(
              (
                (max(Spe_MDS$species) - round(max(Spe_MDS$species)/10,0))
                /3+  round(max(Spe_MDS$species))/10)
              ,0),
            
            round( 
              2* (max(Spe_MDS$species) - round(max(Spe_MDS$species)/10,0))/3  +  round(max(Spe_MDS$species))/10
              ,0),
            max(Spe_MDS$species)
            ), # legend breakpoints
          
          name = paste(   # naming the size legend and pasting the first three letters of the two species name words
            
            substrleft(                    #getting the left characters from a string
              # splitting the species name by "_" and taking 3 letters of the first word
              str_split(species_name_underscore, "_", simplify = TRUE)[,1],3 
            ), 
            
            " ", # pasting space

            substrleft(
              # splitting the species name by "_" and taking 3 letters of the first word
              str_split(species_name_underscore, "_", simplify = TRUE)[,2],3)
          ) 
      
            )+
        
        
    
    # legend design
    
        guides( 
          
          fill = guide_legend( # fill legend
            
            override.aes = list(size = 5),  # change the size of the legend elements
            
            title.theme = element_text(colour = "blue")), # change the colour of the legend title
          
        # size legend: change the fill of the elements
          size = guide_legend(override.aes = list(fill = "gray") ,
                              title.theme = element_text(colour = "blue")) 
        
        )    +
        
    
    
     # add S or F for Strings and Flarks 
    
        geom_text( 
          
          # get one letter from the right of the rownames of the original data 
          label=substrRight(row.names(get(paste(NMDS$data))),1), 
          
          check_overlap = T, size =3.5 # change the size of the letters
          
        ) +
        
    
    
    # plot background 
    
        theme(
          
          panel.background = element_rect(fill= "white", colour= "black")
          
           )+
        
    
    
    # clear the plot from axis
    
        theme(
          
              axis.line=element_blank(),           
              axis.text.x=element_blank(),
              axis.text.y=element_blank(),
              axis.ticks=element_blank(),
              axis.title.x=element_blank(),
              axis.title.y=element_blank())+
        
    
    #
        theme(
          
              legend.key=element_rect(fill="white",),  # get rid of gray legend background
              
              legend.background = element_rect(size=0.5, colour ="black"), # create border around legends
              
              legend.position="right",      # set the legend position to right
              
              plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),        # set the plot title to the left
              
        ) +
        
    
    
    # Add the stress as text to the plot
    
        annotate( 
          "text", # type of annotation
          x=xlim[2]+0.1,
          y=ylim[2]-0.05,
          label= paste("2D Stress:",round(NMDS$stress,2)),  # text to paste, and rounding the stress level with 2 digits
          size = 3.5, # size of the text
          fontface = "bold"
        )+
        
    
    
    # Add the species Name on the bottom right
    
        annotate( 
          
          "text",
          label = paste( gsub(x= species_name_underscore,"_"," ")),
          size = 8,
          x =xlim[2]+ 0.5,
          y=ylim[1]+0.03
                  
        )+
        
    
    
    # Settin up the axis
    
        coord_cartesian( 
          
          xlim =xlim, ylim =ylim
          
          )+ 
        
    
    
    # Add title to plot
    
         ggtitle(
        
        # depending on method used change title accordingly
        
        if(NMDS$call[9]!="Null()")  # if previous best was not used
        {
          
                 paste(" Ordination of", NMDS$data,"with", NMDS$call[9], "model and\n", NMDS$call[8], "used as previous best") 

        }
        
        else                        # if previous best was used
       {
                 paste(" Ordination of", NMDS$data,"with", NMDS$call[8], "model and\n", NMDS$distance, "simillarity used") 

        }
       
       
      )
      
        
      
    
    
    
  # Output the ggplot
  
  print(gg) 
}

As outlined by Vitt et al. other studies found that the relationship between species abundance patterns and water chemistry were especially close for bryophytes. Comparing the ordinations for the bryophyte and vascular plant communities of the flarks we can see that in regard to the spatial area groups, we have a more pronounced clustering and separation for the bryophyte ordination. We have all of the SP1 plots grouped in the top right, most of the SP2 plots in the bottom left quarter and then SP 3 to 5 following the chemical vectors from center to the top right, with SP 3 being more to the center of the ordination. This matches well to what we would expect looking at table 1 in the paper by Vitt et al.. SP 1 and 2 are at the far low end of the chemical gradient and SP3 at the center being closer to SP 4 and 5 but still lower in all parameters and SP 4 and SP 5 beeing quite simmilar in all parameters. This pattern is not as clear for the vascular plants. While we can still see SP 1 and SP 2 at the lower end of the chemical vectorss, we can see no seperation between them and also no pattern within SP 3 to 5. This matches the idea that bryopyhtes are more sensitive to the chemical water chemistry.

12 Summary

The main focus of this work laid in assessing the difference in a global vs a local model and alternative indices vs. the Bray-Curtis index. While the authors used a global model and the Bray-Curtis index we found that using a local model as well as an alternative index can have benefits.

Using a local model generally ended in significantly lower stress values and higher r2 values, which is something to aim for. While the main observations and the interpretation do not change using a local model, we seemingly get an image more closely relating to the put-up hypothesis.

The alternative indices stresswise performed close to the same to the Bray-Curtis index. Although we could see a slightly less clear picture for the full dataset using the euclidean distance, the visual interpretation would not have changed. In some cases (like for the string data) it can make more sense to use an index which better correlates with the environmental data if this is an important part of the analysis. For the String dataset that would have resulted in all chemical vectors being significant.

This work showed the value of assessing different modeling options. Once the Code is set up the amount of extra work to do so is negligible and it can improve the analysis and also the reliability of the results. This is especially true for cases in which the ordination is the central part of a scientific work.

The last part of the work underlined some of the ideas described by Vitt et al.. It also shows the value of further dividing a dataset to achieve a nuanced analysis and get further insight.

It would be interesting to explore the influence of further modeling options like the model options “linear” and “hybrid” and see if they allow for even better results. Also while testing different seeds I realized that the seed can have quite a big influence, especially for the envfit function. It would make sense to find a way to negate this influence.
